# .env.init — Host-side environment variable template
#
# This file is read by host/init-env.sh BEFORE the container starts.
# It resolves OP_*_REF values via the 1Password CLI and writes the result
# to .devcontainer/.env, where Docker Compose picks it up via env_file.
#
# Place this file at the PROJECT ROOT (parent of containers/).
#
# Workflow:
#   1. Copy this file to .env.init and fill in your values
#   2. Run: ./containers/host/init-env.sh
#   3. Start your container: docker compose up
#   4. The container startup script (05-cleanup-init-env.sh) will securely
#      shred .devcontainer/.env after boot — the values are already in the
#      container's environment by that point.
#
# Variable types:
#   KEY=value          — Passed through as-is
#   OP_<NAME>_REF=...  — Resolved via `op read`, exported as <NAME>
#   OP_<NAME>_FILE_REF — NOT supported here (use container-side resolution)
#
# NOTE: OP_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_TOKEN must be in .env.secrets (or your environment),
# not in this file. See .env.secrets.example.

# =============================================================================
# Literal values (passed through unchanged)
# =============================================================================

# TZ=America/Chicago
# ENVIRONMENT=development

# =============================================================================
# 1Password secret refs (resolved at init-env time)
# =============================================================================
# These follow the same OP_<NAME>_REF convention used inside the container,
# but are resolved on the HOST before Docker Compose starts.

# OP_DATABASE_URL_REF=op://Dev/MyApp-DB/connection-string
# OP_API_SECRET_REF=op://Dev/MyApp/api-secret

# =============================================================================
# Direct values (for users without 1Password)
# =============================================================================

# DATABASE_URL=postgres://user:pass@localhost:5432/mydb
# API_SECRET=dev-secret-value
